status_message: The supermoon rises over the Arch in St. Louis as seen from the Compton Hill Water Tower on Sunday. The supermoon will peak on early Monday morning shortly before sunrise, and will be the nearest supermoon in almost 70 years and the largest until Nov. 25, 2034. A supermoon happens when a full moon makes its closest pass to Earth appearing up to 14 percent bigger and 30 percent brighter in the sky. Viewing of the moon should also be good on Monday after the sun sets and the moon rises out of the east. Photo by David Carson, dcarson@post-dispatch.com
link_name: St. Louis Post-Dispatch's cover photo

What started 15 years ago with a soccer team's coat drive has grown into the nonprofit Little Bit Foundation, with boutiques in 25 of the most poverty-stricken schools in St. Louis city and county. The foundation has grown from delivering necessities like socks, underwear and toiletries to providing meals, book fairs, science programs, health screenings and behavioral health interventions.

And some of the schools are reporting better attendance rates, behavior and test scores. Confluence Academy ‚Äî Old North says 98 percent of its kindergarten students were reading at grade level for the first time last year. Attendance has risen to 88 percent at Earl Nance Sr. Elementary School.
link_name: Little Bit Foundation grows into big deal for St. Louis area's poorest kids

Amara Boyd, 7, opens up her ice cream after a press conference where police announced the start of "Operation Polar Cops" at the Boys & Girls Club on North Grand Boulevard on Tuesday, July 26, 2016. The program puts police officers in an ice cream truck handing out free treats to kids to help create positive experiences between the police and the community. The ice cream truck was purchased by the St. Louis Police Foundation at a cost of $16,500. Prairie Farms donated more than 6,000 ice creams to be given away and Schnucks will give the police a discount on future purchases to continue the program. The truck will travel to different areas of the city to hand out ice cream. The idea for the program came from the Boston Police department who have run a similar program since 2007.
Photo by David Carson, dcarson@post-dispatch.com

status_message:
Santa (AKA Danny Wall, from Fenton) cruises down Interstate 70 west through downtown St. Louis on his way to deliver a present to a three-year-old boy in Granite City on Tuesday, Dec. 3, 2013. "I love seeing the expression of joy on people's faces as I drive by" said Wall who started playing the role of Santa Claus eight years ago when his first grandchildren were born. At first he visited just the homes of friends and family but he has visited with groups Boy Scouts, Girl Scouts, and children at Ranken Jordan pediatric hospital. He says playing Santa Claus helps him get the Christmas spirit and relieve stress. Wall is a riding a 2008 Honda Goldwing trike.
Photo By David Carson, dcarson@post-dispatch.com
link_name: St. Louis Post-Dispatch's cover photo

status_message: Several soldiers based at Ft. Leonard Wood pose for a photo with Santa and Mrs. Claus on Saturday, Dec. 20, 2014, at Lambert-St. Louis International Airport as they travel home for the holidays. Several battalions moved through the airport after arriving as early as 1:30 a.m. from the central Missouri Army base. Many of the troops are in the middle of basic training and had been up since 4:30 a.m.Friday before leaving. Photo by Christian Gooden, cgooden@post-dispatch.com

status_message: Workers begin the process of removing ash trees on the south side of the Gateway Arch on Monday, Nov. 3, 2014.  About 800 of the trees, banded with pink ribbons, will be removed starting this week in advance of the arrival of the emerald ash borer beetle, which is expected to destroy many of the trees.  New trees will be planted in 2016 as part of the Arch renovation. Photo by Robert Cohen, rcohen@post-dispatch.com

status_message:
Aniyah Smith (left) , 7, and Brooke Elston, 8, take part in the "World's Largest Swimming Lesson" at the Maplewood Family Aquatic Center on Friday, June 20, 2014.  The event was designed to awareness about the importance of teaching children to swim to help prevent drowning, the Maplewood location had 81 kids take lessons.  2014 was the fifth year The World's Largest Swimming Lesson attempted to break the current Guinness World Record which the organization set last year.  This year's event was aiming to exceed 37,000 lessons for kids, at 900 locations in 26 different countries.  Guinness World Record should take until August to certify the record breaking attempt.
Photo By David Carson, dcarson@post-dispatch.com
link_name: St. Louis Post-Dispatch's cover photo

status_message: In July 1940, the Post-Dispatch published a series of photos of an "auto movie" audience at one of the Midwest's first drive-in theaters. status_message:
For #ThrowbackThursday, a view of the St. Louis skyline in about 1865. Looking eastward from about 16th Street, this view shows numerous steeples. Considered a godless place by early religious visitors, by 1860 St. Louis had 66 houses of worship. The tall spire in the center is First Presbyterian Church, then at 14th and Locust streets. The structure at right with four onion domes is the city's original Central High School. 

Learn more about the burgeoning of St. Louis' spiritual life here: http://postdispat.ch/STLgetsreligion

Missouri History Museum image.
link_name: St. Louis Post-Dispatch's cover photo

status_message:
A special flag that has honored fallen first responders since the terrorist attacks of Sept. 11, 2001, arrived in Missouri today to honor a fallen Columbia, Mo., firefighter.
Members of the International Association of Fire Fighters Local 2665 Honor Guard escorted the United States Honor Flag through Lambert-St. Louis International Airport after arriving from Dallas on Wednesday.
The Honor Flag, conceived in honor of the many fallen first responders to the terrorist attacks on Sept. 11, 2001, will proceed to Columbia, Mo., to be a part of funeral services for Columbia Fire Lt. Bruce Britt.
Britt was killed in the line of duty on Saturday when a walkway collapsed at a University of Missouri-run apartment complex.
Photo by Christian Gooden, cgooden@post-dispatch.com
link_name: St. Louis Post-Dispatch's cover photo

status_message:
St. Louis police motorcycle officers wait for speeding cars on the Oakland Express Highway in November 1953, when the department first began using traffic radar. An officer who monitored the radar transmitter/receiver provided descriptions by radio of speeders to the motorcycle officers. The view is looking west near the intersection with Kingshighway. In the background is St. Louis University's Walsh Stadium, at 5200 Oakland Avenue, which was demolished in 1956. Photo by Arthur Witman of the Post-Dispatch 

Read more about the introduction of the system and see more historic photos in Sunday's Community section or online Saturday at www.STLtoday.com/lookback

status_message:
Excavators stand with the dwindling remains of Big Mound, at North Broadway and Mound Street, in spring 1869. The mound was one of about 25 in a small area north of what is now downtown. They were attributed to the same Mississippian culture that built the mounds in Cahokia. St. Louis once had enough to be nicknamed "Mound City," but one by one they fell to development. Much of Big Mound was used as fill for a railroad line. Now there's just one known mound remaining in the city. 

Read more about Big Mound here: http://bit.ly/BigMound
 
Missouri History Museum photo
link_name: St. Louis Post-Dispatch's cover photo

status_message:
Cardinals rookie Stan Musial slides into third base during the fourth inning of Game 3 of the 1942 World Series at Yankee Stadium on Oct. 3, 1942. Musial came from first base on a single by Walker Cooper. The Cardinals won the game 9-6 and the series 4-1. But celebration was a bit subdued that year, the first Fall Classic during World War II.

Read more about this World Series win with the backdrop of a world war in Sunday's Post-Dispatch, or at www.stltoday.com/lookback on Saturday.

#throwbackthursday

New York Times Co./Getty Images

Bees and butterflies swarm to the flowers next to the lily pond in Tower Grove Park on Wednesday morning. Artist Jim Trapp, 37, from St. Louis, painted the scene in the morning before the heat got to be too oppressive.

Wednesday's high temperature of 98 set a record for Sept. 11, beating by one degree a mark that had held since 1938.
There's a slight chance of showers and a high of 88 expected Thursday as a cool front comes through.
It gets better Friday with a high near 75. A warmup to the mid-80s isn't expected for a week.

Photo by J.B. Forbes, jforbes@post-dispatch.com

status_message:
The St. Louis Police Department's first automobile, shown in 1902. Built by the St. Louis Motor Carriage Co., it was called the "skiddoo car" and used to chase speeders. Powered by a one-cylinder engine, the skiddoo could reach a relatively blistering 25 mph. (The white paint outlining the car was a common device used in newsrooms then by artists to overcome the inadequacies of printing presses and photo reproduction.)

Read about the department's early use of radio to catch crooks in Sunday's Community section and at www.stltoday.com/lookback on Saturday.
link_name: St. Louis Post-Dispatch's cover photo

status_message: St. Louis' own 138th Infantry Regiment returns from World War I with a parade through the city on May 9, 1919. The formation is marching south on 12th Street (now Tucker Boulevard) at Olive Street. The city had erected the pillars to make 12th Street a "hall of honor" for veterans returning from the Great War. The white building at center was home to the Post-Dispatch at the time. Read more about the  138th's homecoming and the formation of the American Legion in St. Louis at http://bit.ly/138homecoming
link_name: St. Louis Post-Dispatch's cover photo

status_message:
This May 4, 1910, photo shows newsies ready to sell newspapers -- including the St. Louis Post-Dispatch. The photo was taken by Lewis Hine as he documented child labor practices -- and abuses -- for the National Child Labor Committee in the early part of the 20th Century. These boys were photographed outside Burley's Branch Office on 23rd Street south of Olive Street. An early depiction of the Weatherbird can be seen on one Post-Dispatch sign. Other papers advertised in the photo are the St. Louis Republic and the St. Louis Globe-Democrat. Photo courtesy of the Library of Congress.
.
link_name: St. Louis Post-Dispatch's cover photo

Did you know St. Louis had a small Chinatown that stood near where the first downtown Busch Stadium was built? It was destroyed in the 1960s as part of efforts to redevelop the area. Busch Memorial Stadium was built nearby, and the block where Chinatown was centered became a parking garage and later an office building. In this photo from 1965, just before the area was leveled, the south leg of the Arch can be seen under construction in the background. The photo was taken looking east down an alley that no longer exists in the block bounded by Market, Walnut, Seventh and Eighth.

Our story on the demise of Chinatown will be in Sunday's Community section and online Saturday at http://www.stltoday.com/lookback

Learn about the building of Busch Memorial Stadium here: http://bit.ly/145I5e1
link_name: St. Louis Post-Dispatch's cover photo

status_message:
In this photo from the Flood of 1993, Lisa Thess of the Pet Adoption Center of St. Charles unloads one of four dogs rescued from the rooftop of a flooded home on Highway 94. John Cottle (left) and Terry Lee of the Missouri Water Patrol clutch two puppies that were saved. 

People had to help animals during the flood, but animals also provided comfort to people who lost almost everything else. See our gallery of animals during the flood at http://bit.ly/floodanimals

Volunteers work to save homes and the nearby Grace Baptist Church in Spanish Lake. The church was built nearly a mile from the Missississippi River, but in 1993, the river grew and grew and grew. In the end, some homes were flooded, but the church and several other homes were saved.

status_message:
Many of you have wondered why we wrote this story, theorizing that our motives were to "race bait," or were part of some undefined liberal conspiracy, or that we simply lost our minds. Let me assure you that we were not attempting to take sides or fan the flames of racial divisiveness. In fact, please note that the story does not take sides. It presents a fair, even-handed, unbiased telling of the details. 
So why did we write about it in the first place? Mr. Olander's letter spurred a response from Schnucks, debate among city leaders, and an order from the city council for the human rights commission to stop meeting with businesses. The letter, in other words, spurred debate and action. That's news. You may not like Mr. Olander's opinion, and you have every right to disagree with him, but it became news. And that's why we wrote the story. Would it have been better for us to simply ignore it? Our job is to shed light on interesting people, topics and debates in the area. That's what we were attemping to do. Thanks for reading.
-- Alan Achkar, Post-Dispatch Metro Editor.
link_name: Dry asparagus prompts questions about racial discrimination in University City : News

status_message:
The Muny has a long history in St. Louis. Here female dancers for the 1942 Muny season strut their stuff in this Post-Dispatch file photo.

More about this photo:
For many years Muny chorus members worked the entire season, not just one or two shows. That meant they started rehearsals before the first show opened, then performed at night and rehearsed their next show during the day.

Most of the 1942 female dancers are from the St. Louis area. From left, by row, they are: (first row) Mary Ann Hickey, Susan Scott, Eunice Kagan, Jean Haumueller, (second row) Rosemary Powell, Leonore Hines, Jane Bauer, Carol Ossman, (third row) Doris Jean Rathman, Virginia Hashagen, Lillian Cross,
Virginia Conrad, (fourth row) Lillian Ann Merod, Virginia Lee Green, Marie von Behren, Betty Herbert, (fifth row) Nancy McCabe, Jackie Bonder, Kay Eibert, Suzanne Schmitz, (last row) Mary Foster, Josephine McCann, Dortha Maie Wicker and Mary Jo Zucchero.
PHOTO BY JACK JANUARY | ST. LOUIS POST-DISPATCH

Louis Abercrombie, a polio patient being treated in an iron lung at St. Anthony's Hospital in St. Louis in November 1949, enjoys a smoke with the help of a nurse during a more lassez faire time for smoking policies. Abercrombie had been in the iron lung, which helped him breathe, for almost three years. The mirror at top allowed him to see visitors.

Dr. Jonas Salk's polio vaccine arrived in St. Louis on this week in 1955, saving countless people from death or disability.

See more photos here: http://tinyurl.com/d7hy7p9

status_message:
The Pacific Local, the commuter train from Pacific, Mo., to Union Station, stops at a station in Webster Groves in January 1946. The Missouri Pacific replaced the steam engines on that daily run in 1952. The Pacific Local, also called the Pacific Eagle, ended service in 1961 as more and more commuters used their automobiles. Post-Dispatch file photo.

See more photos here: http://tinyurl.com/d47dkeg

Read about the last days of the steam engines at www.STLtoday.com on Saturday or in the Community section of Sunday's newspaper.
link_name: St. Louis Post-Dispatch's cover photo

status_message:
U.S. Air Force Staff Sgt. Aaron Blake, 28, walked several miles repositioning flags along the road leading into Highland on Monday, April 1, 2013. Blake and Marine Cpl. Aaron Ripperda, who was among Marines killed in an accident in Nevada, were high school classmates and best friends. Over 2,300 flags lined the route Ripperda's body took to a funeral home on Monday. Visitation is set for Tuesday and Wednesday, with a Mass and burial later on Wednesday.

"I would have walked twenty miles for him," Blake said. "He was my brother in arms."

Photo by J.B. Forbes, jforbes@post-dispatch.com

Read more here:
http://tinyurl.com/bopau6d

status_message: Will 'Punxsutawney Phil' see his shadow?

status_message:
Did you know slavery was abolished in Missouri on Jan. 11, 1865?

Missouri's decision had come in many stumbling and bloody steps. When the Civil War began, 115,000 Missourians were in bondage, most of them in counties along the Missouri River. The governor tried to maneuver the state into the Confederacy, and even among Unionists, some didn't want to free the slaves.

President Abraham Lincoln's Emancipation Proclamation in January 1863 didn't affect states like Missouri that allowed slavery but weren't in rebellion.  But abolitionists in Missouri eventually won the day and the state abolished slavery on Jan. 11, 1865.

Read more here http://tinyurl.com/dx7r9z9 or in Sunday's Post-Dispatch.

This lithograph was produced for the Westliche Post, a German-language newspaper in St. Louis, to honor adoption of Missouri's emancipation ordinance.
link_name: St. Louis Post-Dispatch's cover photo

status_message:
Coal smoke belches from Union Electric's Cahokia power plant on Sept. 16, 1947. Believe it or not, the air was much cleaner in this photo than it was eight years earlier, when coal smoke was so thick in St. Louis on one day that it became known as Black Tuesday. Officials worked for years to clean up the area's notoriously smoggy air.

See more photos and read more about the cleanup effort here:
http://tinyurl.com/arc6n9c

The bridge shown in the picture is the MacArthur Bridge. Busch Stadium and Interstate 64 would be visible in a photo taken from the same location today. Very little of the St. Louis in this picture remains, other than some of the Cupples buildings near Busch Stadium.
link_name: St. Louis Post-Dispatch's cover photo

status_message:
Hi. I'm Derby and I just entered the Cutest Pet Contest, here: http://bit.ly/PDCutestPet 
I was born with microthalmia, which caused me to be blind.  My eyes were removed for my comfort when I was still a kitten, but I don't miss them. My most recent accomplishment is getting on top of the fridge all by myself! My mom adopted me from Tenth Life, and they receive a portion of the contest proceeds (along with my buds at Gateway Pet Guardians and the Humane Society of Missouri).  You should enter!  Okay, I'm off to see if I can master my next feat: toilet paper unrolling.

status_message: Elizabeth Schmidt was reunited with her cat, Satin, at the Humane Society of Missouri on Saturday, July 21, 2012. The cat was rescued earlier in the day from the site of a massive fire that raged through an apartment building at 3949 Lindell Boulevard on Tuesday. Animal cruelty investigators Tim Poorman (right) and Laura Cordes set a trap for Satin, who was seen earlier in the week by apartment staff members who were helping Schmidt salvage her belongings. Satin has only one eye and was adopted by Schmidt from a New York animal shelter. They moved into the apartment building only two weeks ago as Schmidt began a fellowship at Washington University School of Medicine. "She's my little miracle," said Schmidt. "I have my cat. I'm very blessed." Photo by Robert Cohen, rcohen@post-dispatch.com
link_name: Cover Photos

status_message: Jim Jacobs of Ballwin holds his wife Susan Jacobs (right) and family friend Kerri Germann (left) as they kneel at the fallen soldier memorial before the start of the vigil at the steps of Soldiers' Memorial in downtown St. Louis on Friday night. The Jacobs' son Army Sgt. Zachary Fisher was killed in Afghanistan in July 2010. "We decided we could not have his name read without someone from his family here. We had to be here," Jim Jacobs said. The names of the 6,507 service men and women who died in the wars following 9/11 are being read throughout the night. A parade for Iraq war veterans steps off at noon Saturday from Kiener Plaza. Photo by Emily Rasinski
